Corporation
"ISV"        Independent Software Vendor
"J.A."        Joint Appendix
"Microsoft"    Microsoft Corporation
"MS-DOS"    A character-based operating system
developed by Microsoft
"NDA"    Non-Disclosure Agreement
"OEM"    Original Equipment Manufacturer
"OS/2"        A graphical operating system jointly
developed by Microsoft and IBM
"Putative
 Amici"    Anonymous Amici Curiae Represented
by Gary L. Reback, Esq. of Wilson, Sonsini, Goodrich &
Rosati
"Windows"    A graphical operating system developed
by Microsoft


STATEMENT OF JURISDICTION
        Defendant-Appellant Microsoft
Corporation ("Microsoft") appeals from two Orders of the
District Court (Hon. Stanley Sporkin):
(i)    refusing to enter a consent decree, agreed to by
Microsoft and the Antitrust Division of the U.S. Department of
Justice (the "DOJ"), pursuant to the Tunney Act, 15 U.S.C. 
16(b)-(h) (J.A. 1190-91); and
(ii)    permitting certain unnamed software companies (the
"putative amici") and the Computer & Communications
Industry Association ("CCIA") to participate in the proceedings
below pursuant to 15 U.S.C.   16(f)(3) (J.A. 1192-93).
The District Court had subject matter jurisdiction over this
matter pursuant to Section 4 of the Sherman Act, 15 U.S.C.   4,
and 28 U.S.C.    1331 and 1337. The District Court issued the
Orders appealed from on February 14, 1995 (J.A. 1190, 1192),
and Microsoft filed a timely Notice of Appeal on February 16,
1995 (J.A. 1271). See 28 U.S.C.   2107(b).
        This Court has jurisdiction over
Microsoft's appeal from the Order refusing to enter the consent
decree pursuant to 28 U.S.C.   1292(a)(1) because the Order
denies an injunction. The Supreme Court held that the refusal
to enter a consent decree providing for injunctive relief is
appealable under Section 1292(a)(1) if such refusal (i) "might
have a serious, perhaps irreparable, consequence" and (ii) "can
be effectively challenged only by immediate appeal." Carson v.
American Brands, Inc., 450 U.S. 79, 83-84 (1981) (internal
quotation omitted). The Order refusing to enter the consent
decree has the "serious, perhaps irreparable consequence" of
denying Microsoft and the DOJ "their right to compromise
their dispute on mutually agreeable terms," instead subjecting
them to "the costs and uncertainties of litigation." Id. at 87-88.
The Order also "can be effectively challenged only by
immediate appeal" because the opportunity for Microsoft and
the DOJ to settle the case will be irretrievably lost if they are
forced to litigate to final judgment.1

        This Court has jurisdiction over
Microsoft's appeal from the District Court's Order permitting
the putative amici and CCIA to participate in the Tunney Act
proceeding pursuant to 28 U.S.C.   1291 under the collateral
order doctrine of Cohen v. Beneficial Indus. Loan Corp., 337
U.S. 541 (1949). See Kimbro v. Velten, 30 F.3d 1501, 1503
(D.C. Cir. 1994), petition for cert. filed, __ U.S.L.W. ____
(U.S. Nov. 1, 1994) (No. 94-6703). The Supreme Court held in
Cohen that an otherwise non-final order is appealable under
Section 1291 if it "(1) conclusively determine[s] the disputed
question, (2) resolve[s] an important question completely
separate from the merits of the action, and (3) [is] effectively
unreviewable on appeal from a final judgment." United States
v. Weissberger, 951 F.2d 392, 396 (D.C. Cir. 1991) (internal
quotation omitted).
        The Order permitting the putative amici
and CCIA to participate in the Tunney Act proceeding satisfies
this test. First, the Order conclusively determined that the
putative amici and CCIA could participate, over the strenuous
objection of Microsoft and the DOJ (see J.A. 615, 625).
Second, the Order resolved an issue that is both important _
whether persons who flout the requirements of the Tunney Act
and fundamental principles of due process can participate in the
review of a consent decree, thereby preventing its timely entry
_ and is completely separate from the merits, i.e., whether
Microsoft violated the antitrust laws. Third, participation by the
putative amici and CCIA in the proceeding below would be
effectively unreviewable on appeal from a final judgment. By
that time, a settlement that provides the DOJ with more relief
than it could obtain if it prevailed on the merits after trial
(see
J.A. 201 & n.2) would have been lost as a direct result of the
putative amici's and CCIA's interference.

ISSUES PRESENTED FOR REVIEW
        1.    Did the District Court err
in refusing to enter the consent decree by reason of (a) the
scope of review it employed, (b) the scope of disclosure it
required, and (c) the substantive standard of review it applied,
all under the Tunney Act?
        2.    Did the District Court err
in conducting its review under the Tunney Act as a result of
multiple procedural and substantive errors of law, including (a)
reliance on extrajudicial sources of information, (b) acceptance
of belated submissions from persons who filed nothing during
the statutory 60-day comment period, (c) authorization of
individuals to participate in the proceeding on an anonymous
basis, and (d) fundamental mistakes as to the requirements of
the antitrust laws?

STATUTE CONSTRUED
Tunney Act, 15 U.S.C.   16(b)-(h)
(b)    Consent judgments and competitive impact statements;
publication in Federal Register; availability of copies to the
public
        Any proposal for a consent judgment
submitted by the United States for entry in any civil proceeding
brought by or on behalf of the United States under the antitrust
laws shall be filed with the district court before which such
proceeding is pending and published by the United States in the
Federal Register at least 60 days prior to the effective date of
such judgment. Any written comments relating to such
proposal and any responses by the United States thereto, shall
also be filed with such district court and published by the
United States in the Federal Register within such sixty-day
period. Copies of such proposal and any other materials and
documents which the United States considered determinative in
formulating such proposal, shall also be made available to the
public at the district court and in such other districts as the
court may subsequently direct. Simultaneously with the filing
of such proposal, unless otherwise instructed by the court, the
United States shall file with the district court, publish in the
Federal Register, and thereafter furnish to any person upon
request, a competitive impact states which shall recite _
        (1)    the nature and purpose of
the proceeding;
        (2)    a description of the
practices or events giving rise to the alleged violation of the
antitrust laws;
        (3)    an explanation of the
proposal for a consent judgment, including an explanation of
any unusual circumstances giving rise to such proposal or any
provision contained therein, relief to be obtained thereby, and
the anticipated effects on competition of such relief;
        (4)    the remedies available to
potential private plaintiffs damaged by the alleged violation in
the event that such proposal for the consent judgment is entered
in such proceeding;
        (5)    a description of the
procedures available for modification of such proposal; and
        (6)    a description and
evaluation of alternatives to such proposal actually considered
by the United States.
(c)    Publication of summaries in newspapers
        The United States shall also cause to be
published, commencing at least 60 days prior to the effective
date of the judgment described in subsection (b) of this section,
for 7 days over a period of 2 weeks in newspapers of general
circulation of the district in which the case has been filed, in
the District of Columbia, and in such other districts as the court
may direct _
        (i)    a summary of the terms of
the proposal for the consent judgment,
        (ii)    a summary of the
competitive impact statement filed under subsection (b) of this
section,
        (iii)    and a list of the materials
and documents under subsection (b) of this section which the
United States shall make available for purposes of meaningful
public comment, and the place where such materials and
documents are available for public inspection.
(d)    Consideration of public comments by Attorney General
and publication of response
        During the 60-day period as specified in
subsection (b) of this section, and such additional time as the
United States may request and the court may grant, the United
States shall receive and consider any written comments relating
to the proposal for the consent judgment submitted under
subsection (b) of this section. The Attorney General or his
designee shall establish procedures to carry out the provisions
of this subsection, but such 60-day time period shall not be
shortened except by order of the district court upon a showing
that (1) extraordinary circumstances require such shortening
and (2) such shortening is not adverse to the public interest. At
the close of the period during which such comments may be
received, the United States shall file with the district court and
cause to be published in the Federal Register a response to such
comments.
(e)    Public interest determination
        Before entering any consent judgment
proposed by the United States under this section, the court shall
determine that the entry of such judgment is in the public
interest. For the purpose of such determination, the court may
consider _
        (1)    the competitive impact of
such judgment, including termination of alleged violations,
provisions for enforcement and modification, duration or relief
sought, anticipated effects of alternative remedies actually
considered, and any other considerations bearing upon the
adequacy of such judgment;
        (2)    the impact of entry of such
judgment upon the public generally and individuals alleging
specific injury from the violations set forth in the complaint
including consideration of the public benefit, if any, to be
derived from a determination of the issues at trial.
(f)    Procedure for public interest determination
        In making its determination under
subsection (e) of this section, the court may _
        (1)    take testimony of
Government officials or experts or such other expert witnesses,
upon motion of any party or participant or upon its own
motion, as the court may deem appropriate;
        (2)    appoint a special master
and such outside consultants or expert witnesses as the court
may deem appropriate; and request and obtain the views,
evaluations, or advice of any individual, group or agency of
government with respect to any aspects of the proposed
judgment or the effect of such judgment, in such manner as the
court deems appropriate;
        (3)    authorize full or limited
participation in proceedings before the court by interested
persons or agencies, including appearance amicus curiae,
intervention as a party pursuant to the Federal Rules of Civil
Procedure, examination of witnesses or documentary materials,
or participation in any other manner and extent which serves
the public interest as the court may deem appropriate;
        (4)    review any comments
including any objections filed with the United States under
subsection (d) of this section concerning the proposed
judgment and the responses of the United States to such
comments and objections; and
        (5)    take such other action in
the public interest as the court may deem appropriate.
(g)    Filing of written or oral communications with the
district court
        Not later than 10 days following the date
of the filing of any proposal for a consent judgment under
subsection (b) of this section, each defendant shall file with the
district court a description of any and all written or oral
communications by or on behalf of such defendant, including
any and all written or oral communications on behalf of such
defendant, or other person, with any officer or employee of the
United States concerning or relevant to such proposal, except
that any such communications made by counsel of record alone
with the Attorney General or the employees of the Department
of Justice alone shall be excluded form the requirements of this
subsection. Prior to the entry of any consent judgment pursuant
to the antitrust laws, each defendant shall certify to the
district
court that the requirements of this subsection have been
complied with and that such filing is a true and complete
description of such communications known to the defendant or
which the defendant reasonably should have known.
(h)    Inadmissibility as evidence of proceedings before the
district court and the competitive impact statement
        Proceedings before the district court
under subsections (e) and (f) of this section, and the
competitive impact statement filed under subsection (b) of this
section, shall not be admissible against any defendant in any
action or proceeding brought by any other party against such
defendant under the antitrust laws or by the United States under
section 15a of this title nor constitute a basis for the
introduction of the consent judgment as prima facie evidence
against such defendant in any such action or proceeding.

STATEMENT OF THE CASE
A.    Background: The FTC Investigation
        This action arises out of an investigation
commenced by the Federal Trade Commission (the "FTC") in
June 1990. Initially, the FTC's investigation concerned
allegations that Microsoft and International Business Machines
Corporation ("IBM") agreed in 1989 to limit the features of
Microsoft Windows, a graphical operating system, to increase
sales of OS/2, a more complex graphical operating system
jointly developed by Microsoft and IBM. When the
investigation got underway, however, the FTC discovered that
Microsoft was busy developing improved versions of
Windows, making the allegations of collusion completely
untenable. (J.A. 202-03 & n.3)
        Four years ago, the FTC's investigation
was publicly disclosed when a Microsoft competitor told a
securities analyst that it had been interviewed by the FTC Staff.
(J.A. 203) In the week that followed, stories appeared in major
newspapers reporting a wide variety of allegations that had
been made against Microsoft, including that:
(1)    Microsoft intentionally misled competitors about its
plans for Windows so that they would develop applications for
OS/2 instead;
(2)    Microsoft gave its applications developers an unfair
advantage over competitors by providing them with advance
information about new or improved Microsoft operating
systems;
(3)    Microsoft announced a non-existent version of its MS
-DOS operating system with features that matched or beat those
of a new release of DR DOS _ a clone of MS-DOS _ in order
to dissuade OEMs from licensing DR DOS;
(4)    Microsoft obtained confidential information about a new
pen-based operating system from GO Corp. in Microsoft's
capacity as an applications developer and then provided that
information to Microsoft's operating system developers; and
(5)    Microsoft insisted that customers license its applications
in order to obtain MS-DOS and Windows.
(J.A. 203-04)
        The FTC expanded its investigation in
April 1991 and, in August 1991, began requesting documents
from Microsoft and many of its customers on a wide range of
subjects, including the allegations of Microsoft's competitors
reported in the press, as well as the allegations about
Microsoft's licensing practices that ended up in the DOJ's
Complaint. Certain of Microsoft's leading competitors engaged
counsel in Washington, D.C. to press their views on the FTC.
(J.A. 204-06)
        The FTC's investigation culminated in
February 1993 when the Commissioners voted 2-2 on a
recommendation by the Bureau of Competition to initiate an
action in federal court seeking to enjoin certain of Microsoft's
licensing practices. The motion failed for lack of a majority.
(The Bureau of Economics declined to support the Bureau of
Competition's recommendation.) The Commissioners directed
the FTC Staff, however, to pursue a further investigation of
Microsoft relating to allegations that Microsoft had altered
Windows to render the operating system incompatible with
software products produced by Microsoft's competitors. This
investigation proceeded through the spring of 1993, involving
new document subpoenas and more than a dozen additional
depositions of Microsoft officers and employees. (J.A. 207-09)
        In July 1993, the Commission met again
to vote on a recommendation by the Bureau of Competition
(once again, not supported by the Bureau of Economics) to
initiate an administrative proceeding against Microsoft. The
Commission split 2-2 a second time, with the two
Commissioners trained as lawyers again refusing to support an
enforcement action. (J.A. 210)
B.    The DOJ Investigation
        In July 1993, the DOJ, in a virtually
unprecedented step, opened its own investigation of Microsoft
to revisit issues already canvassed in the three-year FTC
investigation. The DOJ secured access to the FTC's
investigative files, including hundreds of thousands of
documents previously produced by Microsoft and third parties.
In October 1993, the DOJ issued its first civil investigative
demand ("CID") to Microsoft, which Microsoft complied with
by mid-January 1994. In February 1994, the DOJ issued a
second CID to Microsoft, covering a wide range of additional
subjects and requiring Microsoft to produce hundreds of
thousands of additional documents. Depositions of senior
Microsoft executives ensued. (J.A. 213-14)
        In June 1994, after nearly a year of
investigation, the DOJ initiated settlement discussions with
Microsoft. From the outset, the DOJ insisted that Microsoft
change its licensing practices for MS-DOS and Windows on
the theory that those practices were preventing competitors
from distributing their operating systems through original
equipment manufacturers ("OEMs"). In particular, the DOJ
insisted that Microsoft stop entering into "per processor"
licenses, under which an OEM had the right to ship MS-DOS
or Windows with _ and paid a royalty to Microsoft for _ all
computers containing particular microprocessor types
designated by the OEM (e.g., Intel 80486DX). The DOJ also
insisted that Microsoft abandon the "minimum commitment"
feature of its license agreements, a mechanism by which
Microsoft provided volume discounts to OEMs based on their
willingness to license a minimum number of copies _ selected
by the OEM _ of MS-DOS or Windows during the term of the
license agreement. In addition, the DOJ wanted Microsoft to
limit the duration of its license agreements to one year. (J.A.
219)
        Settlement discussions between
Microsoft and the DOJ continued into July 1994. At
Microsoft's insistence, the discussions were expanded to
include representatives of Directorate-General IV ("DG IV"),
the competition authority of the European Union. DG IV had
been conducting its own investigation of Microsoft's licensing
practices, an investigation initiated after a broad complaint was
filed against Microsoft by one of its competitors in June 1993.
(J.A. 211) On July 15, 1994, Microsoft entered into a
stipulation with the DOJ _ and simultaneously made an
identical undertaking to DG IV _ agreeing to abandon per
processor licenses and minimum commitments with respect to
MS-DOS, Windows and successor products. (J.A. 30-36)
Microsoft also agreed to reduce the duration of its license
agreements to one year, giving OEMs the option to renew for
one additional year. Microsoft agreed not to tie MS-DOS or
Windows to its applications software (although there was no
claim it had done so previously), and undertook not to license
those operating systems on a flat fee basis. (J.A. 32-26) The
consent decree grants the DOJ extensive monitoring rights to
insure Microsoft's compliance. (J.A. 37-39)
C.    The Tunney Act Review
        The consent decree was filed along with
the Complaint on July 15, 1994. The case was assigned to
Judge Sporkin on July 18, 1994. (J.A. 4) Thereafter, the
consent decree was published in the Federal Register, along
with the DOJ's Complaint and Competitive Impact Statement,
in accordance with the Tunney Act. See 59 Fed. Reg. 42,845
-57 (1994). During the 60-day comment period provided by the
Tunney Act, 15 U.S.C.   16(b) _ which ran from August 20,
1994 through October 18, 1994 _ the DOJ received only five
public comments, none of which came from a significant
participant in the computer software industry. (J.A. 137-54)
Those public comments, along with the DOJ's responses
thereto, were published in the Federal Register as required by
the Tunney Act. See 59 Fed. Reg. 59,426-33 (1994).
    1.    September 29, 1994 Status Conference
        The District Court held a status
conference on September 29, 1994, prior to the conclusion of
the 60-day comment period. Judge Sporkin said that during his
summer vacation he read a book written by two reporters for
the Seattle Post-Intelligencer, James Wallace and Jim Erickson.
(J.A. 85) The book, entitled HARD DRIVE: BILL GATES
AND THE MAKING OF THE MICROSOFT EMPIRE (1992),
alleges, among other things, that Microsoft (i) engages in a
practice called "vaporware" _ that is, the announcement of
nonexistent products to injure competitors _ and (ii) derives
unfair advantages because its applications developers have
access to undisclosed information about Microsoft operating
systems. The District Court emphasized that it was impressed
by the book and its allegations, and said that it wanted matters
raised in the book to be fully vetted in the Tunney Act
proceeding. (J.A. 113)
    2.    November 2, 1994 Status Conference
        At a second status conference on
November 2, 1994, the District Court again dwelled upon the
allegations in HARD DRIVE, eliminating any doubt that the
book had assumed a central role in the Tunney Act proceeding.
        THE COURT: As I said last time, I
happened to read that book. And that book does allege some
very serious practices. Indeed, they cite chapter and verse.
        MS. BINGAMAN: I read the book
myself early in our investigation, as did a lot of people.
        THE COURT: And I want to be satisfied
that _ I would like to be satisfied that, in fact, the person was
writing fiction.
(J.A. 177)
        At the conclusion of the November 2
conference, the District Court told the DOJ to inform interested
persons that they had until December 5, 1994 to seek leave to
participate in the final hearing, then scheduled for December
15, 1994. (J.A. 191) See 59 Fed. Reg. 42,426 (1994). Only one
entity, I.D.E. Corporation, which had submitted a comment
during the statutorily prescribed period, sought leave to
participate in the hearing. (J.A. 601) On December 14, 1994,
the District Court informed the parties that the final hearing
would be delayed until January 20, 1995.
    3.    January 19, 1995 Order
        The day before the final hearing, the
District Court issued an order identifying matters it wanted
counsel to address. (J.A. 1208 n.15) Those matters, including
"vaporware" and purportedly unfair access by Microsoft
applications developers to information about Microsoft
operating systems, came directly out of HARD DRIVE.
    4.    January 20, 1995 Final Hearing
        At the rescheduled final hearing, the
District Court closely questioned counsel for the DOJ and
Microsoft about charges leveled against Microsoft in HARD
DRIVE. The subject of "vaporware" consumed the major
portion of the hearing (J.A. 817-20, 825-30, 846-48, 867-68,
877-84, 893-95, 902-22. 934-35, 938, 944-49, 951-54), even
though the concept is largely unknown to the antitrust laws.
See pages 32-33, infra. The District Court candidly admitted
that it focused on "vaporware" and other issues in its January
19 Order not because they had been alluded to by the putative
amici or CCIA but because they were discussed in HARD
DRIVE.
        THE COURT: I raised these [issues]
before I ever heard from any of these other people [i.e., the
putative amici and CCIA].
        MS. BINGAMAN: Oh, I know you did.
        THE COURT: I mean, I raised these. I
read a book once that raised all these issues, and that's why I
raised them.
(J.A. 855-56)
        Judge Sporkin also made clear that he
was not content to play the traditional role of judge as passive
umpire:
    Unfortunately, I took this role very seriously, and I got
involved in this case. And that's my problem. I got too
involved in this case perhaps. But there are certain things that
are gnawing at me, and I think I gave it to you yesterday in that
Order . . . .
(J.A. 817) When cautioned by counsel for the DOJ about
assuming a prosecutorial role, the District Court complained,
"You just took away my prosecutor's stripes from me." (J.A.
831)
        Based on what he had read in HARD
DRIVE, the District Court told the DOJ that by limiting itself
to the relief provided in the consent decree it was missing an
opportunity to rectify a "mess." (J.A. 846) Operating under the
dangerous misconception that it was dealing with "white collar
crime" (J.A. 827), the District Court made clear that its
approach to rehabilitating Microsoft would be plenary and
uninhibited by legal requirements. Illustrative of its approach is
the following colloquy with counsel for the DOJ, which
followed a summary of the consent decree and the specific
practices to which it was directed.
        THE COURT: You see, what you have to
explain to me is why not if these other practices _ say while
we're cleaning up this mess, why don't we also take care of _
you must agree that vaporware is a problem. You must agree
that to give Microsoft an advantage because their applications
people have access to their operation people [sic] _
        MS. BINGAMAN: Let me go to that.
        THE COURT: In other words, it would
seem to me to say, hey, look, we don't want to come back and
sue you next week. We don't want to sue you every Monday
and Tuesday. You ought to clean up this mess. They've got 50
lawyers there. They can make sure they're doing it.
        MS. BINGAMAN: Here's the answer,
Your Honor. If I had a case that I could file today on those
practices, I would file it. I've said that repeatedly.
        THE COURT: Well, I know, but you
don't have to have a case.
        MS. BINGAMAN: Oh, I do. I am the
Justice Department. For me to stand here and agree to relief
that I didn't include in my complaint because I didn't see the
case, and I can't see it today, _
        THE COURT: Yes, but you're
negotiating with them.
        MS. BINGAMAN: Your Honor, I didn't
negotiate these points because there wasn't a case. I never even
raised these points with them.
        THE COURT: I know that. But you say,
look, you got all these other problems. Why is it _ you know,
it's just good business sense that you don't want the Justice
Department or the Federal Trade Commission to be knocking
on your door every other day. . . . [T]he point I'm saying is I
spent years negotiating consent decrees. Believe me.
        MS. BINGAMAN: About violations you
thought occurred, right?
        THE COURT: I don't know what it was,but I _ don't pin me
down . . . .
(J.A. 846-47)
        As it had at the November 2 conference,
the District Court continued to challenge the DOJ's decision
not to include the allegations from HARD DRIVE in its
Complaint. (J.A. 830). The District Court also pressed for
access to the DOJ's investigative files. (J.A. 856, 945-46)
When the DOJ declined to cede its prosecutorial discretion to
the District Court, the District Court angrily accused the DOJ
of "stonewalling." (J.A. 853-54)
        The District Court permitted the putative
amici and CCIA to participate fully in the final hearing, despite
the fact that they submitted no comments during the 60-day
comment period specified in the Tunney Act and did not take
advantage of the additional period provided by the District
Court for seeking leave to participate in the hearing. The
putative amici filed, anonymously, a lengthy memorandum and
an even lengthier appendix of exhibits _ most of which were
press clippings and none of which was in evidentiary form _
approximately ten days before the final hearing. (J.A. 269, 379)
CCIA first came to the surface when it served papers on
Microsoft and the DOJ late in the afternoon the day before the
hearing. (J.A. 794)
SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
        The District Court's refusal to enter the
consent decree, a decision subject to plenary review by this
Court, was erroneous as a matter of law. First, the Tunney Act
does not authorize the District Court to review allegations
beyond the scope of the DOJ's Complaint. Second, the District
Court's expansive interpretation of its power under the Tunney
Act is not supported by the language of the statute or numerous
cases construing that language. Third, if the Tunney Act did
entitle the District Court to usurp the DOJ's prosecutorial
function, then the statute would be unconstitutional. Fourth, the
District Court's refusal to enter the consent decree will impede
the DOJ's ability to negotiate future settlements.
        The entire Tunney Act proceeding was
undermined by serious procedural errors. First, the District
Court sought out and relied on extrajudicial sources of
information. Second, the District Court allowed parties who did
not comply with procedures specified in the Tunney Act to
disrupt the proceedings. Third, the anonymous appearance of
putative amici curiae violated fundamental principles of due
process and basic rules of practice.
        The District Court's refusal to enter the
consent decree was also based on fundamental mistakes about
the requirements of the antitrust laws. So-called "vaporware" is
not a basis for imposing antitrust liability unless, at a
minimum, the challenged announcement was false or
misleading at the time it was made. This conclusion is not
altered simply because an announcement is motivated by a
desire to increase sales at the expense of competitors. The
documents relied on by the District Court as supposed proof of
Microsoft's use of "vaporware" show nothing more than
legitimate competition.
        The District Court's reliance on
extrajudicial sources of information requires reassignment of
the case on remand to another District Judge.

ARGUMENT
I.
THE DISTRICT COURT'S DECISION HINGES ON A
QUESTION OF LAW SUBJECT TO DE NOVO REVIEW.
        This Court has not previously addressed
the standard of review applicable to an appeal from the refusal
to enter a consent decree under the Tunney Act because it has
never before faced the question _ one indication of the
extraordinary nature of the District Court's decision.2 In
United States v. Western Elec. Co., 993 F.2d 1572, 1578 (D.C.
Cir.), cert. denied, 114 S. Ct. 487 (1993) ("Triennial Review
Remand"), the Court noted that it might be appropriate to
analogize review of a modification of an existing consent
decree to appellate review of a district court's application of
the "substantial evidence" standard. "In that context the district
court decision drops out and the appellate court reviews the
agency decision directly, its sole deference being to the
agency." Id. Here, where the District Court did not conduct an
evidentiary hearing and thus had no basis for drawing factual
inferences or making credibility determinations, this Court
need not defer to any purported "fact finding" by the District
Court. See City of Las Vegas v. Lujan, 891 F.2d 927, 931
(D.C. Cir. 1989); Costello v. Agency for Int'l Dev., 843 F.2d
540, 543 n.5 (D.C. Cir. 1988).3

        This Court can review the materials
properly before the District Court, namely, the Complaint (J.A.
10), the consent decree (J.A. 26), the DOJ's Competitive
Impact Statement (J.A. 58), the five public comments and the
DOJ's responses thereto (J.A. 119), and the affidavits and
memoranda submitted by Microsoft and the DOJ (J.A. 193,
642, 646, 670, 718, 803, 990). From that record, this Court is as
capable as the District Court of determining whether the
consent decree adequately remedies the antitrust violations
alleged in the complaint, the only proper issue in a Tunney Act
proceeding. See United States v. Western Elec. Co., 900 F.2d
283, 293-94 (D.C. Cir. 1990) ("Triennial Review Opinion").
While reviewing a consent decree under the Tunney Act is not
strictly the review of agency action, the same rationale applies
for deferring to the DOJ's (i) assessment of relevant facts
following an extensive investigation, (ii) application of
antitrust law principles to those facts in deciding what claims to
include in the Complaint, and (iii) interpretation of the Tunney
Act based on long experience in implementing the statute. See
Novicki v. Cook, 946 F.2d 938, 941 (D.C. Cir. 1991); see also
Sabine River Authority v. United States Dep't of the Interior,
951 F.2d 669, 678-79 (5th Cir.), cert. denied, 113 S. Ct. 75
(1992).

II.
THE DISTRICT COURT ERRED IN REFUSING
TO ENTER THE CONSENT DECREE.
A.    The District Court Exceeded the Proper Scope
    of Review and Applied the Wrong Standard of
    of Review under the Tunney Act.
        A court's role in reviewing a consent
decree under the Tunney Act is to "determine that the entry of
such judgment is in the public interest," 15 U.S.C.   16(e). In
doing so, the court is not to substitute its judgment for that of
the DOJ in deciding how a case should be settled. To the
contrary, the scope of review under the Tunney Act is quite
limited, and a court must defer to the DOJ's assessment that a
consent decree is adequate unless the court has "exceptional
confidence" that the DOJ is wrong. Triennial Review Remand,
993 F.2d at 1576-77. A court "is not free, in making its public
interest determination, to decide whether the settlement is the
best that could have been reached or, if not, to substitute its
own separate notions as to the proper remedy." United States v.
Waste Management, Inc., 1985-2 Trade Cas. (CCH)   66,651,
at 63,046 (D.D.C. 1985). When viewed against the backdrop of
the DOJ's Complaint, the consent decree in this case is
unquestionably "within the reaches of the public interest."
Triennial Review Opinion, 900 F.2d at 309 (emphasis in
original).4

        Following an exhaustive investigation,
the DOJ filed a Complaint that addressed three practices: (i) the
per processor licensing option for MS-DOS and Windows that
Microsoft made available to OEMs (see J.A. 116-17); (ii) the
minimum commitment feature of Microsoft's license
agreements (J.A. 117); (iii) the two- to three-year duration of
those agreements (see J.A. 118); and (iv) certain non-disclosure
agreements ("NDAs") with a handful of independent software
vendors ("ISVs") that restricted their use of proprietary
information obtained by testing pre-release versions of
Microsoft operating systems (see J.A. 119-21).
        Although Microsoft continues to believe
that none of these practices violates the antitrust laws, it
agreed
to settle with the DOJ to avoid the burden and expense of
further investigation and potential litigation. Consistent with
the consent decree, Microsoft already has (i) stopped offering
per processor licenses to OEMs, (ii) reduced the duration of its
license agreements with OEMs to one year (with the option for
the OEM to renew for one additional year), (iii) eliminated
minimum commitments, and (iv) agreed that confidentiality
restrictions in NDAs relating to specific proprietary
information about operating system software will not extend
for more than one year from receipt of such information by an
ISV or beyond commercial release of the product, whichever
comes first.
        Given the weakness of the DOJ's case
(see J.A. 215 & n.18), the fact that the consent decree abolishes
every single practice challenged in the Complaint is prima facie
evidence that the consent decree is fully sufficient to eliminate
any potential antitrust violations by Microsoft. Even if the DOJ
is correct that Microsoft's licensing practices hindered efforts
by competitors to license their operating systems to OEMs (see
J.A. 842-43) _ a proposition contradicted by the commonsense
observation that OEMs will license any operating system for
which they perceive measurable consumer demand _ then the
problem was eliminated when Microsoft abandoned those
licensing practices more than six months ago (see J.A. 925).
        The District Court rejected the consent
decree because it did not address allegations against Microsoft
that the DOJ had consciously decided not to include in the
Complaint, based on the DOJ's assessment that it had no
prospect of succeeding on those claims (J.A. 836-37). The
allegations of interest to the District Court were contained in
HARD DRIVE, a book with which the DOJ was fully familiar
(J.A. 177), and were echoed in submissions of the putative
amici, whose counsel had brought the allegations to the DOJ's
attention during its investigation (J.A. 867-68). By refusing to
accept the DOJ's considered judgment that allegations other
than those included in the Complaint lacked merit (J.A. 836
-37), the District Court clearly exceeded its power under the
Tunney Act. As the court held in United States v. Airline Tariff
Publishing Co., 836 F. Supp. 9, 12 (D.D.C. 1993) (citations
omitted), "[t]he balancing of competing social and political
interests affected by a proposed antitrust consent decree must
be left, in the first instance, to the discretion of the Attorney
General."
B.    The District Court's Expansive Reading
    of the Tunney Act Is Insupportable.
        As authority for its expansive reading of
the Tunney Act, the District Court pointed to (i) various
statements in the statute's legislative history (J.A. 1218-21),
and (ii) the phrase at the end of Section 16(e) that permits a
court to take into account "any other considerations bearing
upon the adequacy of such judgment" (J.A. 1217).
        The congressional hearings and debates
that preceded enactment of the Tunney Act contain the usual
variety of opinions as to the statute's meaning, none of which
is authoritative. See Joy v. Bell Helicopter Textron, Inc., 999
F.2d 549, 566 (D.C. Cir. 1993). This is especially true of the
testimony of persons who are not members of Congress _ on
which the District Court placed great emphasis. (J.A. 1219)
Such opinions do not necessarily reflect the view of a single
representative or senator, much less the view of Congress as a
whole. Consequently, such testimony has "no conceivable
persuasive effect" because it "reflect[s] nothing more than the
speakers' incomplete understanding of the world upon which
the statute will operate." Fort Stewart Schs. v. Federal Labor
Relations Auth., 495 U.S. 641, 650 (1990).
        The phrase at the end of Section 16(e)
cannot bear the weight with which it was freighted by the
District Court. In interpreting the Tunney Act, the District
Court was not writing on a clean slate. All other courts
interpreting the statute have read it to prohibit the kind of
wholesale incursion on the DOJ's prerogatives committed by
the District Court. See, e.g., United States v. BNS Inc., 858
F.2d 456, 462-63 (9th Cir. 1988) (Tunney Act "does not
authorize a district court to base its public interest
determination on antitrust concerns in markets other than those
alleged in the government's complaint").
C.    The Disclosure Mandated by the District Court,
    If Permissible under the Tunney Act, Would
    Render the Statute Unconstitutional.
        If the Tunney Act did empower courts to
delve into all aspects of the DOJ's investigation of an antitrust
defendant, the statute would raise serious constitutional
questions, under both the separation of powers doctrine and the
due process clause. Other courts construing the Tunney Act
have avoided such problems, recognizing that "where an
otherwise acceptable construction of a statute would raise
serious constitutional problems, the Court [should] construe the
statute to avoid such problems unless such construction is
plainly contrary to the intent of Congress." Edward J.
DeBartolo Corp. v. Florida Gulf Coast Bldg. & Constr. Trades
Council, 485 U.S. 568, 575 (1988); accord Blitz v. Donovan,
740 F.2d 1241, 1244 (D.C. Cir. 1984). Restricting review of a
consent decree to determining whether it remedies antitrust
violations alleged by the DOJ is certainly a "permissible"
reading of the Tunney Act, see Apache Survival Coalition v.
United States, 21 F.3d 895, 904 (9th Cir. 1994), and is
obviously preferable to the one adopted by the District Court,
which gives rise to serious constitutional problems.
    1.    Separation of Powers
        The District Court demanded that the
DOJ provide full details of its investigation, including an
accounting of all charges made by third parties against
Microsoft, whether or not the DOJ concluded that such charges
had merit. (J.A. 1209) That demand is flatly inconsistent with
the separation of powers. Article II grants prosecutorial
discretion to the Executive Branch, while Article III grants
power to adjudicate actual cases and controversies to the
Judicial Branch. It is a principle almost as old as the Republic
that "[t]he province of the court is, solely, to decide on the
rights of individuals, not to inquire how the executive, or
executive officers, perform duties in which they have a
discretion." Marbury v. Madison, 5 U.S. (1 Cranch) 137, 170
(1803).
        In the case of the Tunney Act, such
deference is compelled by the absence of appropriate standards
for a court _ necessarily lacking any factual basis since by
definition there has been no trial _ to substitute its judgment
for
the DOJ's concerning the terms on which a case is settled. As
now Chief Justice Rehnquist warned in discussing review of
consent decrees under the Tunney Act:
    The question whether to prosecute a lawsuit is a
question of the execution of the laws, which is committed to
the executive by Art. II. There is no standard by which the
benefits to the public from a "better" settlement of a lawsuit
than the Justice Department has negotiated can be balanced
against the risk of an adverse decision, the need for a speedy
resolution of the case, the benefits obtained in the settlement,
and the availability of the Department's resources for other
cases.
Maryland v. United States, 460 U.S. 1001, 1006 (1983)
(Rehnquist, J., dissenting). In short, if the District Court does
have sweeping prosecutorial authority under the Tunney Act _
to act, in Judge Sporkin's words, as a "police officer" (J.A.
960) _ then the statute is unconstitutional.
    2.    Due Process
        The District Court's requirement that the
DOJ turn over information developed during the course of its
investigation, even if that information does not evidence an
antitrust violation, raises serious due process concerns. (See
J.A. 1222-23; see also J.A. 111, 171-72) The Constitution does
not permit Judge Sporkin to peruse the DOJ's investigative
files in his chambers while depriving Microsoft of both notice
of the content of those files and an opportunity to respond to
allegations made against it.
    Reliance upon evidence considered in camera as the
basis for decision is fundamentally inimical to due process.
Only the most exceptional circumstances can justify
determinations based upon documents which interested parties
may not examine.
Briscoe v. Kusper, 435 F.2d 1046, 1057 (7th Cir. 1970)
(citations omitted); accord Alderman v. United States, 394 U.S.
165, 180-85 (1969).
        In resisting the broad disclosures sought
by the District Court, counsel for the DOJ attempted to explain
this critical aspect of procedural due process.
    If we want to bring charges against somebody and
contend that they've violated the law, we do so on the basis of
a public record. We present evidence in Court. The defendants
have their chance to rebut that evidence and put on evidence of
their own, and they have a chance to engage in a discussion
about what the requirements of the law are. And we think that
that's a very valuable part of our system.
    If we aren't bringing charges, however, we think it's
fundamentally unfair to the other party to come into Court and
lay on the table suspicions or allegations or innuendo _
(J.A. 179-80) As the DOJ observed, the procedure contemplated
by the District Court would be fundamentally unfair to antitrust
defendants like Microsoft that agree to consent decrees with the
DOJ. (See J.A. 180)
D.    Refusal to Enter the Consent Decree Will Interfere
    with the DOJ's Ability to Negotiate Settlements.
        The District Court's refusal to enter the
consent decree even though it redresses all of the antitrust
violations alleged in the Complaint _ together with the fusillade
of unfounded criticism from the District Court to which
Microsoft has been subjected in the Tunney Act proceeding _
will make other antitrust defendants leery of entering into
consent decrees, thereby hindering the DOJ's ability to obtain
settlements that it regards as favorable. As the Ninth Circuit
cautioned in Bechtel Corp., 648 F.2d at 666, the imposition of
"elaborate requirements" under the Tunney Act "might
undermine the effectiveness of antitrust enforcement by
consent decree." Even the AT&T decision upon which the
District Court relies recognizes that "[i]f courts acting under
the
Tunney Act disapproved proposed consent decrees merely
because they did not contain the exact relief which the court
would have imposed after a finding of liability, defendants
would have no incentive to consent to judgment and this
element of compromise would be destroyed. The consent
decree would thus as a practical matter be eliminated as an
antitrust enforcement tool, despite Congress' directive that it be
preserved." United States v. American Tel. & Tel. Co., 552 F.
Supp. 131, 151 (D.D.C.), aff'd sub nom. Maryland v. United
States, 460 U.S. 1001 (1982).
        These concerns apply with even greater
force to settlements that the DOJ negotiates in conjunction with
other antitrust enforcement agencies. For example, the consent
decree here is identical in all material respects to an
undertaking made simultaneously by Microsoft to DG IV. The
District Court's refusal to enter the consent decree will
undercut the ability to negotiate similar multilateral agreements
in the future because DG IV and other foreign antitrust
enforcement agencies will be wary of indeterminate outcomes
in protracted Tunney Act proceedings.

III.
    SERIOUS PROCEDURAL ERRORS INFECTED
    THE ENTIRE TUNNEY ACT PROCEEDING.
        In reviewing the consent decree under the
Tunney Act, the District Court committed a variety of
procedural errors so egregious that they undermined the
integrity of the entire proceeding, providing further reason to
reverse the District Court's erroneous conclusion that the
consent decree is not in the public interest.
A.    The District Court Improperly Sought Out and
    Considered Extrajudicial Sources of Information.
    1.    HARD DRIVE
        From the very outset, Judge Sporkin's
views about Microsoft were shaped by HARD DRIVE. Judge
Sporkin readily admitted that _ after learning that this case had
been assigned to him _ he read the book in order to learn about
Microsoft: "I was on vacation in the library and thought it
would be a good idea maybe to know as much about Microsoft
as they're going to know about me." (J.A. 92) It was bad
enough that Judge Sporkin credited allegations in a book
riddled with factual inaccuracies, which Microsoft had no real
opportunity to rebut. It was worse still to make HARD DRIVE
the centerpiece of the proceeding.
        Instead of focusing on the Complaint, the
consent decree, the DOJ's Competitive Impact Statement, the
public comments and the DOJ's responses to those comments,
the District Court focused on HARD DRIVE. The following
colloquy with counsel for the DOJ is emblematic of this
approach.
        THE COURT: Over the summer I happen
[sic] to read HARD DRIVE. I don't know. Have you read that
book?
        MR. RUSSELL: No, I haven't, Your
Honor.
    . . .
        THE COURT: [A]s I read the book, it
doesn't seem to be one that's trying to be unfair. I mean, it
seemed to be somewhat balanced. They seemed to think that
the company had done a lot of good things. But there are a
number of practices, and I gather that this _ what peaks my
interest is from my old SEC days, but things like putting out
announcements that are misleading or not true to freeze the
competition, something called vaporware. I don't know what
that is. Maybe you've heard of it.
        MR. RUSSELL: I know the term very
well, yes.
        THE COURT: And I don't know that's
true or not. But if they're doing that, I think you ought to look
into it.
(J.A. 85) The topic of "vaporware" dominated the Tunney Act
proceeding even though (i) the DOJ _ following an extensive
investigation _ decided not to include a "vaporware" allegation
in the Complaint and (ii) liability has never been imposed
under the antitrust laws based solely on the use of "vaporware."
See pages 32-33, infra.
        When the DOJ asked Judge Sporkin
whether his reading of HARD DRIVE had given rise to
"specific concerns" other than "vaporware," he responded,
"Well, you read the book. They're all there." (J.A. 91) Upon
learning that Microsoft's counsel had not read HARD DRIVE
either, Judge Sporkin suggested that "everybody [should] read
the book and maybe we'd get on the [same page]." (J.A. 97-98)
It is apparent that in Judge Sporkin's mind, a book based
largely on conversations with Microsoft's competitors and
disgruntled former employees had replaced the Complaint as
the yardstick against which the sufficiency of the consent
decree was to be measured.
        Fixated on HARD DRIVE, the District
Court repeatedly asked the DOJ and Microsoft about
allegations made in the book during the two status conferences
that preceded the final hearing. (See, e.g., J.A. 85-86, 89, 91
-93, 97-98, 107-09, 113, 177-78, 188-89) What Judge Sporkin
really wanted to know was whether the authors of HARD
DRIVE were correct in alleging that Microsoft:
    (i)     intentionally "pre-announced" software
products still under development to deter the purchase of
competitors' products (the "vaporware" allegation) (see J.A.
85-86, 97-98, 177-78);
    (ii)    misappropriated proprietary information
about new software products being developed by smaller
companies by engaging them in sham merger negotiations (see
J.A. 91-92); and
    (iii)    took unfair advantage of the fact that it
develops both operating systems and applications that run on
those operating systems (see J.A. 107-09).
The DOJ properly refused to indulge Judge Sporkin's curiosity
about these allegations, which are both unfounded and wholly
unrelated to the Complaint.
    2.    Inadmissible Evidence
        Judge Sporkin's reliance on improper
sources of information was not limited to reading HARD
DRIVE on his summer vacation. He gave credence to a 100
-page submission by the putative amici (J.A. 269), a document
replete with conclusory assertions that have no factual support
whatsoever or are allegedly supported by the uninformed
speculation of news reporters (J.A. 379). Ignoring the
admonition that one should "[n]ever believe in mirrors or
newspapers,"5 the District Court cited things written about
Microsoft in "the Press over the years" as authority for factual
assertions in its opinion. (J.A. 1235 & n.36)

        During the final hearing, Judge Sporkin
asked counsel for the putative amici to "interpret" for him two
documents they had submitted that were incomplete (and
irregular) on their face and were never admitted into evidence.
(J.A. 879-84) This was necessary because Judge Sporkin had
no idea what the documents meant. As he explained, "the only
reason I need an interpretation is because this uses a language
I'm not familiar with." (J.A. 881-82) Expressing concern about
the "schnook consumer . . . thinking of buying the
TurboCharge" (a term from the automotive industry without
meaning in the computer software industry), Judge Sporkin
seemed unaware that the documents relate to programming
languages like TurboBASIC that are used by professional
software developers to create applications software. Such
programming languages are not operating systems, the only
products at issue in the Complaint. (J.A. 915-16) Having heard
no testimony from anyone with first-hand knowledge of the
documents or the events they describe, Judge Sporkin
announced that the documents were "conspiratorial" (J.A. 917)
_ although other members of the "conspiracy" were not named
_ and proved that Microsoft uses "vaporware" as an
anticompetitive weapon (J.A. 949-50).6

    3.    Ex Parte Communications

        In response to the DOJ's request at the
end of the final hearing that the District Court entertain no
more tardy submissions from third parties, Judge Sporkin said:

    If somebody throws over the transom _ we used to have
transoms around here _ some more documents [like those] that
Reback gave me, I'm not going to just say, hey, I can't see
them and throw them away. It would be like a police officer
who gets a report of a crime and says I'm off duty. Go and see
somebody else. I can't do that.
(J.A. 960) Apart from reflecting a profound misconception
about the proper role of judges in our legal system, see Jeffrey
S. Shaman, JUDICIAL CONDUCT AND ETHICS   5.10, at
114 (1990), this statement was interpreted by Microsoft's
competitors _ not surprisingly _ as an open invitation to
communicate with the District Court on an ex parte basis.
Several such communications were readily forthcoming.
    (1)    Emboldened by Judge Sporkin's
statement, the putative amici filed a supplemental submission
on January 31, 1995 to which they attached a document that
was redacted in its entirety from the copies of the submission
served on Microsoft and the DOJ. (J.A. 1002)
    (2)    Apple Computer, Inc. ("Apple"), a
Fortune 100 company, had no
compunction about sending directly to Judge Sporkin's
chambers on February 13, 1995 a letter and five affidavits that
accused Microsoft of various anticompetitive actions unrelated
to the Complaint. Incredibly, those materials were neither
served on the parties nor filed with the Clerk of the Court.7

    (3)    Andrew Shulman, a software industry
commentator who writes for magazines willing to publish his
views, faxed a letter directly to Judge Sporkin's chambers in
which he opposed entry of the consent decree and announced
that he had instructed his publisher to send a copy of his latest
book, Unauthorized Windows 95, to Judge Sporkin. Judge
Sporkin did not disclose receipt of Mr. Shulman's letter or the
book. It was only when the putative amici attached Mr.
Shulman's letter to a supplemental submission (J.A. 1039-41)
that Microsoft even learned of its existence, prompting
Microsoft to question how much other information came to
Judge Sporkin without the knowledge of Microsoft or the DOJ.
        Such ex parte communications are not
customary in the courts of this nation _ for reasons too obvious
to merit extended discussion. As the court observed in In re
Paradyne Corp., 803 F.2d 604 (11th Cir. 1986), ex parte
communications "conflict with a fundamental precept of our
system of justice: a fair hearing requires 'a reasonable
opportunity to know the claims of the opposing party and to
meet them.'" Id. at 612 (quoting Morgan v. United States, 304
U.S. 1, 18 (1938)).8

        Mr. Shulman is not a lawyer and perhaps
does not know any better, but the secret transmission of
information to Judge Sporkin's chambers by lawyers for the
putative amici and Apple was clearly unethical. See D.C. Rules
of Professional Conduct, Rule 3.5; see also Henry S. Drinker,
LEGAL ETHICS 78 (4th ed. 1963) ("A lawyer may not
properly give a memorandum to the trial judge without a copy
to the other side, even where the court asked for it.").
B.    The District Court Allowed Improper
Parties to Disrupt the Proceedings.
        The Tunney Act expressly provides that
public comments on a consent decree are to be submitted
within 60 days following the DOJ's publication of the consent
decree in the Federal Register. See 15 U.S.C.   16(b). That
comment period is fully "adequate to permit [individuals] a full
and fair opportunity to present their views on relevant antitrust
considerations bearing upon entry of the proposed final
judgment." United States v. Stroh Brewery Co., 1982-2 Trade
Cas. (CCH)   64,782, at 71,829 (D.D.C. 1982). While the
Tunney Act contains provisions for shortening the 60-day
comment period, 15 U.S.C.   16(d), that period may not be
extended "absent a request to do so from the government."
United States v. Airline Tariff Publishing Co., 1993-1 Trade
Cas. (CCH)   70,191, at 69, 894 (D.D.C. 1993). The DOJ made
no such request here.
        The 60-day comment period reflects
Congress' view that information necessary to decide whether a
consent decree is in the public interest should be adduced
"through the least complicated and least time-consuming means
possible." H.R. Rep. No. 93-1463, 93d Cong. 2d Sess. 8
(1974), reprinted in 1974 U.S.C.C.A.N. 6535, 6539. Failure to
adhere to the 60-day comment period would permit third
parties to "unduly delay or prejudice the original parties,"
United States v. G. Heileman Brewing Co., 563 F. Supp. 642,
649 (D. Del. 1983), precisely what the putative amici and
CCIA have done here.
        The period for public comment on the
consent decree commenced on August 20, 1994 and expired on
October 18, 1994. Nearly three months later, and only ten days
before the final hearing, the putative amici submitted a 100
-page memorandum commenting on the consent decree. Not to
be outdone, CCIA waited until the day before the final hearing
to file its motion to intervene or, in the alternative,
participate
as an amicus curiae. Even though these submissions were
clearly untimely under Section 16(b), the District Court
permitted both the putative amici and CCIA to file papers and
present arguments at the final hearing pursuant to Section
16(f)(3), which authorizes the court to allow "appearance as
amicus curiae" or "participation in any other manner and extent
which serves the public interest as the court may deem
appropriate."
        The District Court reasoned that
requiring individuals to submit comments within the 60-day
period specified in Section 16(b) would effectively read
Section 16(f)(3) out of the Tunney Act. (J.A. 1206) It is the
converse that is true, i.e., permitting individuals to submit
comments right up to the final hearing renders the 60-day
public comment period meaningless. As an elementary rule of
construction, "[a] statute should be construed so that effect is
given to all its provisions, so that no part will be inoperative
or
superfluous, void or insignificant, and so that one section will
not destroy another unless the provision is the result of obvious
mistake or error." 2A Norman A. Singer, STATUTES AND
STATUTORY CONSTRUCTION   46.06, at 119-20 (5th ed.
1992); see Consolidated Rail Corp. v. United States, 896 F.2d
574, 579 (D.C. Cir. 1990). The only way to give effect to both
Section 16(b) and Section 16(f)(3) is to limit participation as
amicus curiae or otherwise pursuant to Section 16(f)(3) to
individuals who have submitted a timely public comment. Such
a reading also promotes the interest in open proceedings that
underlies the Tunney Act, insuring that all comments on a
consent decree and the DOJ's responses to those comments are
published in the Federal Register and thus disseminated to the
public at large.
        Even if a court could authorize
individuals who submitted nothing during the 60-day comment
period to participate pursuant to Section 16(f)(3) on proper
notice to the parties, calculated efforts by competitors of an
antitrust defendant to disrupt a settlement at the last minute
should not be condoned. The injudicious atmosphere prevailing
at the final hearing _ with center stage given to persons making
unsubstantiated accusations based on press reports _ makes a
mockery out of the Tunney Act's scheme for the orderly and
efficient review of consent decrees.
C.    The District Court Wrongly Permitted
Parties to Appear Anonymously.
        It is a fundamental precept of American
jurisprudence that parties to litigation are entitled to confront
those accusing them of misconduct. See Southern Methodist
Univ. Ass'n of Women Law Students v. Wynne & Jaffe, 599
F.2d 707, 713 (5th Cir. 1979). As a result, the general rule is
that the identity of an amicus curiae must be disclosed. See
Robert S. Stern, et al., SUPREME COURT PRACTICE   13.3,
at 563 (7th ed. 1993).
        The ability to proceed anonymously is
limited to those rare situations in which there is an unusual
concern for protecting personal privacy or a material risk that a
person will suffer physical harm. See Doe v. Frank, 951 F.2d
320, 324 (11th Cir. 1992). Potential embarrassment or
economic harm is not a sufficient justification for allowing a
litigant to proceed anonymously. See National Commodity &
Barter Ass'n v. Gibbs, 886 F.2d 1240, 1245 (10th Cir. 1989).
See generally 2A James W. Moore & Jo D. Lucas, MOORE'S
FEDERAL PRACTICE   10.02, at 10-8 to 10-10 (1994).
        The District Court credited the bald
assertion of the putative amici _ almost certainly large software
companies _ that they were appearing anonymously because
they feared retaliation from Microsoft. (J.A. 1213) There was
no evidentiary support for that assertion. Even if there were,
however, such fear is not a sufficient basis for permitting a
litigant to proceed anonymously. See Wynne & Jaffe, 599 F.2d
at 713.
        The District Court stated that "[i]t is
preferable for persons to identify themselves to permit the
Court to ascertain any bias on their part." (J.A. 1213) That is
not "preferable;" it is necessary. Aside from the obvious due
process issue of denying Microsoft a right to confront its
accusers, the District Court's acceptance of the putative amici's
cloak-and-dagger tactics flatly contradicted basic rules of
practice.
        First, Rule 109 of the Rules of the U.S.
District Court for the District of Columbia expressly requires
that counsel disclose the corporate affiliations of their clients.
That rule serves the dual purposes of (i) allowing the court and
the parties to ascertain the need for recusal based on financial
interests of the court in corporate litigants, see D.C. Cir.
I.O.P.
IX(A)(3) ("the Court will not accept an amicus brief where it
would result in the recusal of a member of the panel"); and (ii)
enabling the court to enforce ethical rules that proscribe
conflicts of interest on the part of lawyers, see D.C. Rules of
Professional Conduct, Rule 1.7. Microsoft has no way of
knowing whether Judge Sporkin owns securities issued by the
putative amici, and neither does their counsel or Judge Sporkin
himself.
        Moreover, the law firm representing the
putative amici has never explained how it can act as regular
outside counsel for Novell, Inc. (and have a partner on Novell's
board of directors) while, at the same time, directly attacking
Microsoft's planned acquisition of Intuit (J.A. 70-72) in which
Novell has a substantial interest as the purchaser of a personal
finance software product to be divested by Microsoft. That
important ethical question has simply been swept under the rug
by the District Court.
        Second, persons filing amicus briefs are
typically required to set forth the nature of their interest in
the
litigation. See, e.g., Fed. R. App. P. 29. Such a statement is
expressly required by the rules of this Court. See D.C. Cir.
I.O.P. IX(A)(3). Of course, it is impossible to assess the alleged
interest of the putative amici here because they refuse to
disclose their identities.
        Finally, and more fundamentally,
allowing the putative amici to oppose entry of the consent
decree without requiring them to disclose their role in the
computer software industry contradicts the Tunney Act's goal
of exposing the process by which consent decrees are approved
to public scrutiny. The bias and interest of parties seeking to
block approval of a consent decree are critical to evaluating the
merits of their position. That is not possible, however, unless
they disclose who they are.

IV.
THE REFUSAL TO ENTER THE CONSENT DECREE
WAS BASED ON FUNDAMENTAL MISCONCEPTIONS
ABOUT BASIC PRINCIPLES OF ANTITRUST LAW.
        The District Court readily acknowledged
that the consent decree "deals with [the] licensing and non
-disclosure practices that the Government found to be
anticompetitive," i.e., the only antitrust violations alleged in
the
Complaint. (J.A. 1227) The District Court refused to enter the
consent decree, however, because it "does not address . . . a
number of other anticompetitive practices that from time to
time Microsoft has been accused of engaging in by others in
the industry." (J.A. 1227) Of these allegations _ none of which
was proven in the Tunney Act proceeding and all of which are
beyond the scope of the Complaint _ the District Court was
"particularly concerned about the accusations of 'vaporware.'"
(J.A. 1228) That concern runs directly counter to the law
regarding so-called "product pre-announcements."
A.    Product Announcements Violate the Antitrust Laws
Only
    If They Are Knowingly False or Misleading When
Made.
        The District Court defined "vaporware"
as "the public announcement of a computer product before it is
ready for market for the sole purpose of causing consumers not
to purchase a compe
titor's product that has been developed and is either currently
available for sale or momentarily about to enter the market."
(J.A. 1228) Throughout the proceeding below, Microsoft and
the DOJ told Judge Sporkin that product announcements do not
violate the antitrust laws unless they are knowingly false or
misleading when made. (See J.A. 205 n.12, 648-49, 994-95;
see also J.A. 826, 901-02, 912) The District Court dismissed
this as a "funny little interpretation of vaporware" (J.A. 914)
and a "rather narrow view of this highly questionable practice"
(J.A. 1231). To the contrary, it is a straightforward statement of
legal principles.
        The leading case on product "pre
-announcements" is MCI Communications Corp. v. American
Tel. & Tel. Co., 708 F.2d 1081 (7th Cir. 1981), modified,
1983-2 Trade Cas. (CCH)   65,520 (7th Cir.), cert. denied, 464
U.S. 891 (1983). A month after MCI announced its plan to
provide nationwide long distance service, AT&T announced a
new long distance pricing scheme, called the "Hi-Lo" tariff,
and sought permission from regulators to utilize it. Id. at 1099.
Hi-Lo did not become effective until fifteen months later,
however, because of delays in obtaining regulatory approval.
Id. MCI challenged, inter alia, AT&T's "early" announcement
of Hi-Lo, claiming that AT&T "knowingly misled the public
into believing that the new tariff would be implemented
without 'undue delay.'" Id. at 1128.
        The Seventh Circuit rejected MCI's "pre
-announcement" claim, pointing out that "[i]t is certainly not
unusual for competitors to announce a new product, service or
price before its actual introduction in the market." Id. at 1129.
The court also noted that similar "pre-announcements" had
been upheld in a variety of factual contexts. Id. The decided
cases, the court continued, "suggest that AT&T's early
announcement of Hi-Lo must be found to be knowingly false
or misleading before it can amount to an exclusionary
practice." Id. (emphasis added). The court added that a more
restrictive rule would "inhibit the flow of valuable information
to the market [and] risk infringing upon protected commercial
speech and first amendment rights." Id. at 1128. Although it
was not disputed that AT&T's goal in announcing the Hi-Lo
tariff was to dissuade customers from switching to MCI, the
court concluded that there was "insufficient evidence to support
a finding of unlawful pre-announcement" because "[n]either
AT&T's application to the FCC for permission to file the Hi
-Lo rate, nor the accompanying press release contains any false
or misleading information about Hi-Lo or its availability." Id.
at 1129 & n.69.9

        In ILC Peripherals Leasing Corp. v.
International Business Machs. Corp., 458 F. Supp. 423 (N.D.
Cal. 1978), aff'd sub nom. Memorex Corp. v. International
Business Machs. Corp., 636 F.2d 1188 (9th Cir. 1980), cert.
denied, 452 U.S. 972 (1981), the court applied an identical
standard to a "pre-announcement" claim in the computer
industry. In that case, Memorex challenged, inter alia, the
accuracy of IBM's announcement that an improved control
program for external disk drives called NCP was expected to
be made available to customers by March 1973. Id. at 441. The
court concluded that "there was nothing knowingly false about
the NCP announcement," despite the fact that "actual delivery
of NCP slipped six months to October 1973." Id. at 442.
"[D]elivery slippages," the court noted, "are not uncommon for
complex new products in the computer industry." It was
dispositive, in the court's view, that there was "no evidence to
suggest that when IBM announced NCP for delivery in March
1973, it did not honestly expect the product to be available at
that time." Id. See also 3 Philip Areeda & Donald F. Turner,
ANTITRUST LAW   738i, at 284 (1978).10

B.    An Otherwise Legitimate Product Announcement

    Is Not Rendered Illegal Merely Because It Is Motivated

    by a Desire to Capture Sales from a Competitor.

        Despite this uniform authority, the
District Court insisted that announcing a product in advance of
its commercial release _ even if not deceptive or misleading _
is somehow improper if the announcement is motivated by an
intent to divert sales from a competitor. (See J.A. 1232; see
also J.A. 912, 918-19) This cannot be the law, for it would
punish companies for pursuing a goal that, fairly speaking,
motivates the entire free market system, namely, to capture
each and every sale possible through the use of all legitimate
means available. Any other conclusion would turn the Sherman
Act into a refuge for the inefficient rather than a tool for
promoting competition. See Northeastern Tel. Co. v. American
Tel. & Tel. Co., 651 F.2d 76, 87-88 (2d Cir. 1981), cert.
denied, 455 U.S. 943 (1982).
        All product announcements are
motivated, at least in part, by a hope that once consumers know
their options, they will elect to purchase improved products
still under development. Such announcements inform
consumers' purchasing decisions; they do not, and cannot,
"freeze" sales of competing products. (See J.A. 1229) It is even
less plausible to contend that such announcements "freeze"
development of competing products. (See J.A. 1232) On the
contrary, the announcement that a product is slated for
commercial release at some future time acts as a spur to
competitors to accelerate development of their own products,
an unambiguously procompetitive outcome.
        At its most basic level, "[c]ompetition
consists of winning business from rivals." MCI
Communications, 708 F.2d at 1113. Even a monopolist _
which Microsoft is not _ is free to compete for every last
sale.11 Because the antitrust laws were intended to encourage
vigorous competition, a desire by Microsoft to persuade
consumers to purchase its products instead of its competitors'
products cannot render otherwise legitimate conduct illegal. As
the First Circuit noted in Barry Wright Corp. v. ITT Grinnell
Corp., 724 F.2d 227, 232 (1st Cir. 1983) (Breyer, J.), focusing
on an intent to increase sales at the expense of competitors does
not work "in a world where executives may think no further
than 'Let's get more business,' and long-term effects on
consumers depend in large measure on competitors'
responses."
        Consequently, the antitrust laws focus on
whether challenged conduct is anticompetitive.
    Anticompetitive conduct is conduct without legitimate
business purpose. Such conduct makes sense only because it
eliminates competition. Acts which are ordinary business
practices typical of those used in a competitive market do not
constitute anticompetitive conduct violative of Section 2.
Trace X Chem., Inc. v. Canadian Indus., Ltd., 738 F.2d 261,
266 (8th Cir. 1984), cert. denied, 469 U.S. 1160 (1985). The
notion that anything intended to have "an adverse impact on a
competitor's product" (J.A. 1232) is anticompetitive is
dangerously misguided; it would proscribe broad categories of
ordinary business conduct, such as advertising, sales
promotions and new product development.
C.    The Documents Relied on by the District
    Court Do Not Support Its Conclusions.
        As support for its conclusion that
Microsoft utilizes "vaporware," the District Court pointed to
portions of two performance evaluations of a Microsoft
employee dating from 1987 (and a page of handwritten notes of
unknown origin) that were submitted by the putative amici
(J.A. 1230-31) _ documents that the District Court
characterized as "smoking gun[s]" (J.A. 826). In fact, the
documents depict nothing more than Microsoft's legitimate
efforts to accelerate development of new programming
language products in response to competitive products from
Borland.
        Borland announced that it was
developing TurboBASIC on November 20, 1986. (J.A. 910) In
response, Microsoft accelerated development of QuickBASIC
3.0, which Microsoft started shipping one week before Borland
started shipping TurboBASIC on April 1, 1987. (J.A. 910)
Whatever benefit was derived from being first to introduce a
new version of BASIC thus rightfully belonged to Microsoft,
not Borland, because QuickBASIC 3.0 won the product
development _ as opposed to the product announcement _ race.
        Borland also had a programming
language product called TurboC. In June 1987, Microsoft
announced that it was developing two competing products _
QuickC and C 5.0 _ and predicted that those products would be
available to consumers in four months. Microsoft missed that
objective by one month, shipping both products in October
1987. (J.A. 911) Microsoft's announcement, which was neither
false nor misleading when made, was motivated by a proper
business purpose, namely, to inform software developers that
Microsoft was hard at work on products with features and
functionality superior to those of the Borland product.

V.
THE DISTRICT COURT'S CONSIDERATION OF
EXTRAJUDICIAL INFORMATION REQUIRES THAT THE
CASE BE REMANDED TO ANOTHER DISTRICT JUDGE.
        Microsoft has been severely prejudiced
by the District Court's decision to gather facts outside the
record of the Tunney Act proceeding. See Price Bros. v.
Philadelphia Gear Corp., 629 F.2d 444, 446 (6th Cir. 1980).
Although it had a duty to avoid extrajudicial information that
might influence its decision, the District Court actively sought
out such information, first by reading HARD DRIVE and then
by inviting the putative amici and others to provide it with
information on an ex parte basis.12

        Furthermore, the District Court's failure
to disclose whether it had received Mr. Shulman's letter or his
book (and perhaps other ex parte communications) _ and the
absence of any statement by the District Court that it neither
read nor considered such information _ is very troubling. See
pages 25-26, supra. Canon 3A(4) of the Code of Judicial
Conduct expressly states that "[a] judge should . . . neither
initiate nor consider ex parte or other communications
concerning a pending or impending proceeding." Consideration
of such ex parte communications by a judge is a basis for
disqualification. Authority for that proposition is scant, but
only because the practice is so improper that the issue does not
often arise. See United States v. Van Griffin, 874 F.2d 634, 637
(9th Cir. 1989); McFadden v. United States, 63 F.2d 111, 112
(7th Cir. 1933); see also 13A Charles A. Wright, et al.,
FEDERAL PRACTICE AND PROCEDURE   3543, at 586
(1984).
        Under 28 U.S.C.   455(b)(1), a judge is
required to disqualify himself "[w]here he has a personal bias
or prejudice concerning a party, or personal knowledge
concerning disputed evidentiary facts concerning the
proceeding." In addition, a judge is required under 28 U.S.C. 
455(a) to disqualify himself when, as an objective matter, his
"impartiality might reasonably be questioned." See Liljeberg v.
Health Servs. Acquisition Corp., 486 U.S. 847, 856-60 (1988);
In re Barry, 946 F.2d 913, 916 (D.C. Cir. 1991) (Edwards, J.,
dissenting). Under both of these provisions, it is improper for a
judge to proceed with a case if he has formed an adverse
opinion about a litigant based on information obtained from an
extrajudicial source such as HARD DRIVE. See Liteky v.
United States, 114 S. Ct. 1147, 1155-57 (1994). That, however,
is exactly what Judge Sporkin said he did.
        By engaging in its own fact gathering, the
District Court assumed the inquisitorial role of a European
investigating magistrate, a clear basis for disqualification. See
Jeffrey S. Shaman, supra,   6.07, at 159-60. Indeed, less
egregious conduct has led to the disqualification of a judge.
See, e.g., In re School Asbestos Litig., 977 F.2d 764, 784 (3d
Cir. 1992) (disqualifying judge who attended seminar at which
13 of plaintiffs' 18 expert witnesses made presentations similar
to their anticipated trial testimony).
        Whether or not this Court concludes that
the District Court's conduct requires disqualification under 28
U.S.C.   455, the case should be reassigned to another district
judge on remand to avoid even the appearance of impropriety.
See Calvaresi v. United States, 348 U.S. 961, 961 (1955). The
Court can order such reassignment under its statutory power to
"require such further proceedings to be had as may be just in
the circumstances." 28 U.S.C.   2106; see Liteky, 114 S. Ct. at
1156-57; United States v. Torkington, 874 F.2d 1441, 1447
(11th Cir. 1989). This Court has not hesitated in the past to
reassign a case to a different district judge where the district
court's opinion reflects "the personal views of the author" as
opposed to an application of judicial precedents, see Naples v.
United States, 307 F.2d 618, 629 (D.C. Cir. 1962) (en banc), or
where the district court showed such disregard for established
procedures that the fairness of the proceeding has been called
into question, see Bishop v. United States, 349 F.2d 220, 221
-22 (D.C. Cir. 1965), cert. denied, 393 U.S. 870 (1968).
        The gratuitous and unsupported
assertions by the District Court that Microsoft (i) is represented
by internal and external counsel who are not "credible" (J.A.
929), (ii) is unlikely to comply with the consent decree (J.A.
933), (iii) is routinely counseled to violate the law (J.A. 932
-34), (iv) might destroy relevant evidence (J.A. 884), and (v)
has become "robotized" and does not "understand[ ] how it
should act with respect to the public interest and the ethics of
the market place" (J.A. 1237) would lead any reasonable
observer to conclude that _ despite having heard no testimony
and having reviewed no admissible evidence _ Judge Sporkin
predetermined the merits of this case based on "independent
research" he did outside the courthouse. In order to restore the
integrity of these proceedings, the case should be remanded to
another district judge. See Alexander v. Primerica Holdings,
Inc., 10 F.3d 155, 164-65 (3d Cir. 1993); Louis Vuitton S.A. v.
Lee, 875 F.2d 584, 590 (7th Cir. 1989).

CONCLUSION
    A.    Because this Court owes no deference to
the District Court's conclusion that the consent decree is not in
the public interest, the Order should be reversed with a
direction that the consent decree be entered forthwith in its
present form. As this Court held in Gas Appliance Mfrs. Ass'n
v. Department of Energy, 998 F.2d 1041, 1045 (D.C. Cir.
1993), there is no need to remand to a district court for
application of the proper legal standard when the appellate
court is in as good a position as the trial court to review the
administrative record directly.
    B.    Because Judge Sporkin has demonstrated
personal bias against Microsoft that he acquired by considering
information obtained outside the Tunney Act proceeding, this
Court should remand the case to a different district judge to
enter the consent decree and address any issues that may arise
in the future regarding Microsoft's compliance with the
consent decree. See Judith R. v. Hey, 405 S.E.2d 447, 452-54
(W. Va. 1990) (remanding case to different trial judge because
original trial judge formed opinions on factually disputed
issues based on information obtained outside judicial setting).
    C.    If the case is remanded on any other
basis, the Court should instruct the District Court about the
scope of review of consent decrees under the Tunney Act,
including proper procedures to be observed in light of the due
process clause, the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure and other
applicable rules, and the Tunney Act.
    D.    The submissions of the putative amici
and CCIA should be stricken from the record for failure to
comply with the requirements of the Tunney Act, and the
putative amici's attempt to appear anonymously in violation of
basic principles of due process and applicable
court rules should be rejected. For the same reasons, their briefs
on this appeal should be stricken, and they should not be
allowed to participate in oral argument.
Dated:    New York, New York
    March 7, 1995
                   
    Respectfully submitted,
                   
