-------------FOOTNOTES---------------
    1    In a typical litigation, an order denying
an injunction adversely affects only the party that sought
injunctive relief, and therefore only that party can appeal the
order under Section 1292(a)(1). See Liberty Mut. Ins. Co. v.
Wetzel, 424 U.S. 737, 744-45 (1976) (dictum). That principle
has no application here, however, because both parties to the
consent decree are equally aggrieved by the District Court's
refusal to enter it. But see EEOC v. Pan Am. World Airways,
796 F.2d 314, 316 (9th Cir. 1986), cert. denied, 479 U.S. 1030
(1987).
    2    See ABA Antitrust Section,
ANTITRUST LAW DEVELOPMENTS 573 & n. 193 (3d ed.
1992) (citing only one reported decision in which a court
refused to enter a consent decree under the Tunney Act).
    3    The District Court's bald assertion that
Microsoft is illegally maintaining a "monopoly position" (J.A.
1226) is symptomatic of the errors that result when purported
"fact finding" occurs in an evidentiary vacuum. Apparently
proceeding on the mistaken idea that it was ruling on a motion
to dismiss under Fed. R. Civ. P. 12(b)(6), the District Court
assumed the truth of all of the allegations in the Complaint.
The consent decree, however, expressly provides that it does
not constitute an admission by Microsoft of anything (J.A. 26),
and Microsoft emphatically denies that it possesses monopoly
power, i.e., the power to set prices or exclude competition, in
any segment of the computer software business.
    4    Accord, e.g., United States v. Bechtel
Corp., 648 F.2d 660, 666 (9th Cir.) ("The court's role in
protecting the public interest is one of insuring that the
government has not breached its duty to the public in
consenting to the decree. The court is required to determine not
whether a particular decree is one that will best serve society,
but whether the settlement is 'within the reaches of the public
interest.'") (citations omitted), cert. denied, 454 U.S. 1083
(1981); United States v. Gillette Co., 406 F. Supp. 713, 716 (D.
Mass. 1975) ("It is not the court's duty to determine whether
this is the best possible settlement that could have been
obtained if, say, the government had bargained a little harder.
The court is not settling the case. It is determining whether the
settlement achieved is within the reaches of the public
interest.").
    5    John Osborne, The Hotel in Amsterdam,
Act. I (1968).
    6    The two documents later became the
cornerstone of the District Court's conclusion that truthfully
announcing products in advance of their commercial release is
"anticompetitive" (J.A. 1232) and "deceitful on its face" (J.A.
1236), a conclusion that makes no sense and is belied by the
documents themselves. See pages 35-36, infra.

    7    Judge Sporkin said he did not consider
the attachment to the putative amici's supplemental submission
(J.A. 1210) or the Apple materials in reaching his decision
(J.A. 1210-11), but he did not say he had not read them.
    8    Accord Jeffrey S. Shaman, supra,   5.10,
at 114 ("In the American legal system, facts are to be
determined on the basis of evidence presented in court within
the adversary process so that each side can present its version
of the facts . . . . Prior personal knowledge of facts may cause a
judge to predetermine a case or to evaluate facts on a one-sided
basis.").
    9    The decision in United States v.
American Tel. & Tel. Co., 524 F. Supp. 1336 (D.D.C. 1981), is
not to the contrary. In denying AT&T's motion to dismiss, the
court simply pointed to, among other things, evidence that
AT&T had announced Digital Data Service ("DDS") _ a
service AT&T had previously considered and rejected _ a full
two years before AT&T made the service available to
customers. Id. at 1356. At the time AT&T announced DDS in
response to a competitor's announcement of a similar service,
DDS was truly a non-existent product because AT&T had not
even begun to develop it. Id. at 1365 n.118.
    10    For unilateral action like "vaporware" to
be an antitrust violation, it must constitute monopolization or
attempted monopolization under Section 2 of the Sherman Act.
15 U.S.C.   2. The District Court completely ignored this legal
requirement. See Southern Pac. Communications Co. v.
American Tel. & Tel. Co., 556 F. Supp. 825, 966 n.168
(D.D.C. 1982) ("there is no evidence in the record from any
customer that the so-called 'preannouncement' of Hi/Lo caused
that customer to decline to order service from plaintiffs or to
delay ordering service from plaintiffs"), aff'd, 740 F.2d 980
(D.C. Cir. 1984), cert. denied, 470 U.S. 1005 (1985); Ronson
Patents Corp. v. Sparklets Devices, Inc., 112 F. Supp. 676, 689
(E.D. Mo. 1953) ("There is no substantial evidence that a single
customer of [the plaintiffs'] products ever read the ad or that
[the plaintiffs] lost a single sale by it.").
    11    See Ball Memorial Hosp., Inc. v. Mutual
Hosp. Ins., Inc., 784 F.2d 1325, 1339 (7th Cir. 1986)
("Vigorous competitors intend to harm rivals, to do all the
business if they can.").
    12    See Jeffrey S. Shaman, supra,   6.01, at
149-50 ("At the very least, participation in ex parte
communications will expose the judge to one-sided
argumentation, which carries the attendant risk of an erroneous
ruling on the law or facts. At worst, ex parte communication is
an invitation to improper influence if not outright corruption.").
