<A HREF="/map/library.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/library.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Library" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>The following order sets out guidelines for expedited litigation in the federal government's challenge to the proposed merger of the Microsoft Corp. and Intuit Inc.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
NORTHERN DISTRICT OF CALIFORNIA


UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,
Plaintiff,

vs.

MICROSOFT CORPORATION and
INTUIT INCORPORATED,
Defendants.

No. C-95-1393 WHO

PRETRIAL ORDER
NUMBER 1



After plaintiff, United States of America, filed its complaint on
April 27, 1995, alleging that the proposed acquisition of
defendant Intuit Incorporated by defendant Microsoft Corporation
would violate Section 7 of the Clayton Act, 15 U.S.C. section 15,
the parties appropriately agreed that the public interest demands
a speedy resolution of the important legal and factual questions
raised inherent in the dispute. To accomplish this purpose, the
parties entered into a stipulation, annexed hereto as Exhibit A,
providing procedures designed to expedite trial preparation and
shorten the length of trial and expedite the appellate process,
The parties left it to the Court to determine whether the pretrial
preparation should take six or eight weeks from the date of filing
the complaint and whether at trial each party would take one week
or two weeks to present its case. Accordingly,

IT IS HEREBY ORDERED that:

1. The hearing on plaintiff's motion for a preliminary injunction,
pursuant to Rule 65(a)(2) of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure
is consolidated with a trial on the merits that will commence on
Monday, June 26, 1995, at 8:30 a.m.

2. Plaintiff and defendants jointly will each have no more than
forty-five (45) trial hours to present their case, including both
direct and cross-examination of witnesses and presentation of
legal arguments to the Court. Cross-examination time will run
against the party or parties cross-examining the witness rather
than against the time of the party who called the witness.

3. The Court will be in session from 8:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m. Monday
through Thursday, including two fifteen (15) minute breaks.

4. A pretrial conference will be held on Thursday, June 22, 1995,
at 10:00 a.m.

5. In accordance with the Stipulation,

a. The parties will submit an agreed confidentiality stipulation
and protective order to the Court for its approval by May 3, 1995.


b. Defendants will answer the complaint by May 12, 1995.

c. All discovery will be completed by no later than June 16, 1995,
with the exception of discovery directed to plaintiff's rebuttal
expert witnesses, if any.

d. Plaintiff has no present intention of serving requests for the
production of documents on defendants, but reserves the right to
do so on a limited basis if (a) defendants put in issue matters
not covered by plaintiff's previous discovery demands, or (b) such
requests are directed to matters or events occurring since
defendants' previous document productions. Plaintiff may serve a
maximum of twenty (20) contention interrogatories if they are not
duplicative of interrogatories contained in plaintiff's previous
Civil Investigative Demands and Requests for Additional
Information and Documents under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust
Improvements Act of 1976.

e. Defendants jointly will propound a maximum of twenty-five (25)
written interrogatories and twenty-five (25) requests for
production of documents to plaintiff.

f. The parties will respond to all written interrogatories and
will produce documents responsive to all document production
requests within seven (7) days of receipt, and will inform the
opposing party or parties promptly of any objections to such
discovery demands.

g. Plaintiff will have the right to depose any person on
defendants' list of trial witnesses. In addition, plaintiff can
take a maximum of four (4) additional full-day depositions of
current employees of either of the defendants.

h. All depositions will be limited to a single day and, unless
otherwise agreed between the parties, will commence at 9:00 a.m.
and will conclude no later than 5:00 p.m. Depositions of current
employees on defendants' list of trial witnesses who have been
deposed previously will be limited to five (5) hours of testimony.


i. By May 3, 1995, the parties will exchange lists for trial,
including both live and deposition witnesses. The witness lists
will include a statement of topics to be addressed in the
testimony of each witness. The witness lists for plaintiff and for
defendants jointly will each include no more than twenty (20) live
witnesses, including any subsequent supplementation. The witness
lists may be supplemented by adding the name of any person who is
thereafter deposed no later than forty-eight (48) hours after the
close of his or her deposition. The witness lists may also be
supplemented on a limited basis in good faith until June 14, 1995.
Thereafter, no supplementation of witness lists will be permitted
except by leave of the Court for compelling cause shown.

j. The parties will exchange proposed stipulations of
uncontroverted facts by May 5, 1995, and will negotiate in good
faith to finalize those stipulations as soon as practicable.

k. The parties will exchange designations of portions of
transcripts or videotapes of depositions to be used at trial no
later than June 14, 1995. Such designations by plaintiff and by
defendants jointly will not exceed five hundred (500) transcripts
pages (or the equivalent in videotape excerpts). The parties will
exchange counter-designations relevant to the portions of the
transcript designated by the opposing party or parties and will
interpose objections to those designations no later than June 17,
1995. The parties will interpose objections to such
counter-designations no later than June 20, 1995.

l. The parties shall endeavor to make their trial witnesses or
other persons under their control available for deposition within
seventy-two (72) hours of the date on which the deposition is
originally noticed. Any person not ultimately available for
deposition by subpoena or otherwise who was not previously deposed
in circumstances where counsel for one of the defendants was
permitted to attend and cross-examine may not be called as a
witness at trial.

m. No later than June 12, 1995, the parties will exchange lists of
exhibits to be used at trial. The parties will stipulate as to the
admissibility of all such exhibits except as to relevance,
materiality and cumulativeness, unless a good-faith objection is
raised concerning authenticity or hearsay within five (5) days
following receipt of the list. The exhibit lists may be
supplemented on a limited basis in good faith until June 19, 1995,
and any good-faith objections to such supplementation must be
raised by no later than June 23, 1995.

n. All charts, diagrams or other graphic evidence will be included
in the Exhibit list. Any such graphic evidence created thereafter
shall be furnished to the opposing party or parties within
forty-eight (48) hours after its preparation and in no event less
than twenty-four (24) hours before it is offered in evidence.

o. Plaintiff will designate all expert witnesses and provide
defendants with all reports prepared by those witnesses no later
than June 5, 1995. Defendants will designate all expert witnesses
and provide plaintiff with all reports prepared by those witnesses
no later than June 9, 1995. Plaintiff will designate any rebuttal
expert witnesses and provide defendants with all reports prepared
by those witnesses no later than June 13, 1995. The parties may
depose expert witnesses designated by the opposing party or
parties, subject to the one-day limitation noted previously.

p. Plaintiff will serve and file a pretrial memorandum no later
than June 14, 1995. Defendants will serve and file a pretrial
memorandum no later than June 21, 1995.

q. No later than June 16, 1995, the parties will submit the
pretrial statements required by Local Rule 235.7, including the
previously agreed stipulation of uncontroverted facts.

r. All motions in limine will be filed no later than June 16,
1995, and all responses to such motions will be filed no later
than June 21, 1995. If the Court finds that five (5) days is
inadequate time to address all motions in limine, the trial date
will be postponed to accommodate the Court's schedule.

s. All correspondence, court papers (excluding voluminous
attachments) and discovery requests will be served by facsimile as
well as by overnight courier. Documents received after 4:00 p.m.
Pacific Daylight Time shall be deemed to have been received the
following day.

6. A list of exhibits, with a brief statement following each
exhibit that describes its substance or purpose and the identity
of the sponsoring witness shall be prepared in accordance with
Local Rule 235-7(j), and shall be prepared on a form substantially
similar to the form annexed hereto as Exhibit B. The exhibits
shall be numbered consecutively. Plaintiff's exhibits shall
commence with "Exhibit No. 1" and defendants' exhibits shall
commence with "Exhibit No. "1000." Each party's exhibits shall be
marked with the exhibit tags annexed hereto as Exhibit C.

7. The originals and two copies of the exhibits (in loose-leaf
binders with tabs) shall be lodged with the Clerk's Office. In
addition, at trial counsel shall have one set of exhibits for
their own use and one set for the witnesses.

Any document lodged with the Clerk's Office shall be delivered to
the Clerk's Office in boxes or binders clearly marked with the
caption and number of the case, the name(s) of the party(ies)
lodging the document(s) and the contents of the box(es) and/or
binder(s). A notice of lodging shall be filed with the Court.

If there is any difficulty with the Clerk's Office in the lodging
of documents required by this Order, please ask the filing clerk
in the Clerk's Office to contact the Judge's Court Clerk or to
call his chambers for clarifications.

8. Plaintiff shall serve and file with the Court proposed findings
of fact and conclusions of law no later than June 21, 1995. The
findings of fact shall set forth in simple declarative sentences,
separately numbered, all factual contentions relied upon by the
party in support of its claim for relief. Such findings of fact
shall, so far as possible, contain no color words, labels, or
legal conclusions, and shall be set forth so as to enable the
opposing party to set forth the counterfindings required.

9. Defendants shall file counterfindings of fact and conclusions
of law numbered to correspond with the opposing party's findings
of fact and conclusions of law. The counterfindings of fact shall
set forth in simple, declarative sentences, separately numbered,
all factual contentions relied upon by the party. Such
counterfindings shall, so far as possible, contain no color words,
labels, or legal conclusions, and shall set forth only the party's
contentions as to the same factual matters set forth in the
opposing party's corresponding findings of fact of the same
number. Additional findings of fact and conclusions of law, upon
which the party relies and as to which the plaintiff has not set
forth a contention, shall also be set forth. Such additional
findings and conclusions shall follow and be numbered
consecutively with the party's counterfindings and conclusions
that correspond to the opposing party's findings and conclusions.
Defendants' counterfindings shall be filed no later than June 26,
1995.

10. The Court clarifies its suggestion to counsel with respect to
communications with the media and suggests that as officers of the
Court they exercise sound discretion in responding to any media
questions.

Dated: May 2, 1995.

/s/
William R. Orrick
United States District Judge
</PRE>
